  How NetFPGA Controls the FIFO — Actual Protocol

  The real NetFPGA protocol is push-based, not pull-based. Looking at user_data_path.v and
  gpu_wrapper.v:

  The Actual Signals (from user_data_path.v)

  in_data[63:0]   IN    64-bit data (NOT 72 — ctrl is separate!)
  in_ctrl[7:0]    IN    8-bit control word
  in_wr           IN    "I have valid data this cycle"
  in_rdy          OUT   "I can accept data" (backpressure)

  out_data[63:0]  OUT   64-bit data
  out_ctrl[7:0]   OUT   8-bit control word
  out_wr          OUT   "I have valid data for you"  ← THIS IS THE ANSWER
  out_rdy         IN    "Downstream can accept"

  The Protocol

  Input (receiving packets):
  Data transfers when:  in_wr == 1  AND  in_rdy == 1
  Your module asserts in_rdy when it has space.

  Output (sending packets):
  Data transfers when:  out_wr == 1  AND  out_rdy == 1
  Your module asserts out_wr when it has data to send.
  Downstream asserts out_rdy when it can accept.

  What gpu_wrapper.v Currently Does

  Lines 76-79 reveal something important — it's a passthrough!

  assign out_data = in_data;
  assign out_ctrl = in_ctrl;
  assign out_wr   = in_wr;
  assign in_rdy   = out_rdy;

  The GPU wrapper doesn't touch packets at all right now. It just passes them through the
  pipeline and uses the register interface (generic_regs) for the host PC to load programs
  and data into the GPU via software registers.

  What Needs to Change for Option 3

  The convertible_fifo uses the wrong signal names and bundles ctrl+data into 72 bits. For
  the real NetFPGA pipeline, you need an output FSM that drains the FIFO after processing:

  IDLE:
    out_wr = 0
    wait for cpu_packet_done → go to SEND

  SEND:
    out_wr = 1
    out_data = fifo_bram[head_ptr][63:0]
    out_ctrl = fifo_bram[head_ptr][71:64]
    if (out_rdy):
      head_ptr++
      if (head_ptr == tail_ptr) → go to IDLE

  Updated Architecture

  NetFPGA pipeline                              NetFPGA pipeline
     in_data/ctrl/wr ──►┌──────────────┐◄── out_rdy
     in_rdy ◄───────────│  Input FSM   │───► out_data/ctrl/wr
                         │  (write to   │
                         │   FIFO)      │    Output FSM
                         └──────┬───────┘    (drain FIFO
                                │             after GPU done)
                          FIFO BRAM
                         Port A │ Port B
                           │         │
                          CPU       GPU

  So there's a missing piece — you need a small output controller FSM that reads from the
  FIFO and drives out_wr/out_data/out_ctrl with proper handshaking. The current
  convertible_fifo assumes someone externally drives out_rd_en, but in the real pipeline your
   module must be the one asserting out_wr.

